# Define function for evaluation
def evaluate(y_te, pred, labels, return_data = False):
    
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_te, pred, labels)

    print("\nConfusion matrix (absolute):")
    cm_abs = pd.DataFrame(data = cm, index = labels, columns = labels)
    cm_abs = pd.concat([cm_abs], keys=['True'], names=[''], axis = 0)
    cm_abs = pd.concat([cm_abs], keys=['Predicted'], names=[''], axis = 1)
    display(cm_abs)

    print("\nConfusion matrix (relative):")
    cm_rel = pd.DataFrame(data = cm / cm.sum(), index = labels, columns = labels)
    cm_rel = pd.concat([cm_rel], keys=['True'], names=[''], axis = 0)
    cm_rel = pd.concat([cm_rel], keys=['Predicted'], names=[''], axis = 1)
    cm_rel = round(cm_rel * 100, 2)
    display(cm_rel)

    print("\nClassification report:\n")
    class_report = classification_report(y_true = y_te, y_pred = pred)
    print(class_report)

    acc = round(accuracy_score(y_true = y_te, y_pred = pred), 4)
    print("Overall accuracy: {}".format(acc))
    f1 = round(f1_score(y_true = y_te, y_pred = pred, average='weighted'), 4)
    print("Overall f1_score: {}".format(f1))
    
    if return_data == True:
        return({'cm_rel': cm_rel, 'cm_abs': cm_abs, 'class_report': class_report, 'acc': acc, 'f1': f1})

1. Text Retrieval¶

A data set with the target variables is imported. Every row represents one 8-K filing. The data is already prepared by me, so that it can be merged with the corresponding 8-K filings later on. For this purpose, every row also contains the CIK, the Ticker, the Date Filed and the Filename. There are two target variables, Y_cont and Y_disc, but we will focus on these later.

To get the text data, you need to do make one request for each 8-K file. I recommend to get the raw data first and to do the data cleaning later. That way, you will always have access to the raw data and you can easily experiment with different data cleaning methods without having to repeat any requests.

2. Text Pre-Processing¶

We now have the downloaded 8-K filings and one CSV file with the target variables for each filing. We have to process the raw texts of the filings to make them usable for modelling. The goal is to get one CSV file containing both, the target values and the processed text, for all 8-K filings. The data is imported again (since this part of the notebook is probably run at a later time point, after the time consuming download from section 1).

2.1 Example¶

For this section, we make use of the amazing library spaCy. If you haven't already, you might have to install it following the descriptions on the official website: https://spacy.io/usage If you encounter issues, check your spacy version and your python version to ensure they work well together.

The documents contain some cases where there is a PDF inserted in the bottom of the 8-K filing. This part is removed with the code below Handle special cases, as we are only interested in text data before the PDF. Essentially, the data is then processed as follows:

  1. Read the downloaded 8-K file as text file
  2. Handle special cases (remove PDF from text)
  3. Remove HTML tags
  4. Get raw text (without tabs, spaces, newlines etc.)
  5. Tokenize with spaces (alternatively with SpaCy)
  6. Take lower-case lemmatized non-stop words with only alphabetical characters and length > 1
  7. Create one string with space-separated lemmas

Note that the result of step 4 is saved separately as "raw" text later on in the data frame. Steps 5-7 are independent from step 4, i.e. they also build on step 3, and their result is saved as "text" later on in the data frame.

Before we do the processing for all 8-K filings, let's illustrate it with only 1 filing. Feel free to print out the results after each step yourself. I did not define a function for this to make it easier for you to play around with it.

Ideally, we would like to apply the below processing for all documents. However, this is not possible because the text in tokens = nlp(text) cannot have more than 1 Mio. characters. There are some very large documents with more characters .Therefore, we later need to approach these large documents differently. For now, we just mark them as "large".

2.2 Process all 8-K filings¶

Now, we process all documents as described in the example above to get one CSV file containing both, the target values and the processed text, for all 8-K filings. Also the raw text is included (only with removal of new lines, tabs etc.).

Note that the total filesize for all the raw 8-K filings is approx 50GB. After processing, the size will be smaller. Still, we might get memory issues. Therefore, we split the processing into 5 batches of approx. 10GB each. Furthermore, there are some 8-K filings that have too many characters. SpaCy can only handle a maximum of 1M characters when performing tokenization. When we encounter these large 8-K filings, we just mark them as "large" so that we can exclude them later on.

# Create directory for adjusted files
path = "input/adj"
if not os.path.exists(path):
    os.makedirs(path)

# Special escape elements to be removed
pattern = re.compile(u"(\ud83d[\ude00-\ude4f])|"  # emoticons
                   u"(\ud83c[\udf00-\uffff])|"  # symbols & pictographs (1 of 2)
                   u"(\ud83d[\u0000-\uddff])|"  # symbols & pictographs (2 of 2)
                   u"(\ud83d[\ude80-\udeff])|"  # transport & map symbols
                   u"(\ud83c[\udde0-\uddff])"  # flags (iOS)
                   "+", flags=re.UNICODE)
        
# Process each batch one at a time
for b, df_batch in zip(range(len(batches)), batches):

    N = df_batch.shape[0]
    df_batch["large"] = False
    cnt = 0
    
    for i, row in df_batch.iterrows():
        
        filename = df_batch.loc[i, "Filename Local"]
        
        # Read the downloaded 8-K file as text file
        with open("input/raw/filings/{}".format(filename), "r") as f:
            text = f.read()
            
        try:

            # Handle special cases (remove PDF from text)
            s = re.search(">GRAPHIC", text)
            if s != None and s.span()[0] > 500:
                text = text.split(">GRAPHIC")[0]
            text = text.split("PDF OF ENTIRE FORM 8-K")[0].split("<DESCRIPTION>PRINTABLE 8-K ")[0]

            # Remove HTML tags
            soup = BeautifulSoup(text, "html.parser")
            text = soup.get_text(separator = " ")

            # Remove special escape elements
            text = pattern.sub(r' ', text)

            # Pre-process text of non-large files
            if len(text) <= 1e6:
                
                # Get raw text (without tabs, spaces, newlines etc.)
                df_batch.loc[i, "raw"] = " ".join(text.split())

                # Tokenize with SpaCy
                tokens = nlp(text)

                # Take lower-case lemmatized non-stop words with only alphabetical characters and length > 1
                lemmas = [token.lemma_.lower() for token in tokens 
                          if not token.is_stop if token.is_alpha if len(token) > 1]

                # Create one string with space-separated lemmas
                text = " ".join(lemmas)

                # Save the result
                df_batch.loc[i, "text"] = text

            else:
                df_batch.loc[i, "large"] = True
                
        except:
            
            df_batch.loc[i, "error"] = True
            print("\n ERROR:")

        # Print status (comment this in, if you want status updates)
        cnt += 1
#         print("{} | {} | {} / {} | {} | {} | {} | {}".format(b, i, cnt, N-1, filename, row["Company Name"], 
#                                                             row["Ticker"], row["Date Filed"]))

    # Export data
    df_batch.to_csv("{}/target_withalltext_batch{}.csv".format(path, b), index = False)

It seems like the size of the processed files is small enough to concatenate them into one file.

Later, it might be good to know, which 8-K events each filing actually contains (https://www.sec.gov/fast-answers/answersform8khtm.html). Therefore, let's extract this information from the text data. Note that I added this section later. Hence, it's separate from section 2.2. You could also integrate this task into 2.2.

4. Negation Encoding¶

In [0]:
# Encode Negation
for i, row in tqdm(df.iterrows()):

    # Take raw text
    text = row["raw"]

    # Negate words
    text = re.sub(r"\b(?:not|'t|never|no|neither|nor|nobody|noone|nothing|nowhere|cannot)\b[\w\s]+[^\w\s]", 
                   lambda match: re.sub(r'(\s+)(\w+)', r'\1NEG_\2', match.group(0)), text, flags=re.IGNORECASE)

    # Other pre-processing
    try:

        if len(text) <= 1e6:

            # Tokenize with SpaCy
            tokens = nlp(text)

            # Take lower-case lemmatized non-stop words with only alphabetical characters and length > 1
            lemmas = []
            for token in tokens:
                if token.text[0:4] == "NEG_":
                    neg_token = nlp(token.text[4:])[0]
                    if (not neg_token.is_stop and neg_token.is_alpha and len(neg_token) > 1):
                        lemmas.append(token.lemma_.lower())
                else:
                    if (not token.is_stop and token.is_alpha and len(token) > 1):
                        lemmas.append(token.lemma_.lower())

            # Create one string with space-separated lemmas
            text = " ".join(lemmas)

            # Save the result
            df.loc[i, "text_neg"] = text

        else:
            df.loc[i, "large"] = True

    except:
        df.loc[i, "error"] = True

5.1 Normalization¶

Before we can actually use the data, we need to normalize it using the S&P 500, a stock price index with the 500 largest publicly traded companies in the US. The reason for this is that we want to only classify the stock price changes that happened because of the 8-K filings (and not because of the overall market trend). Therefore, we have to remove the effect of the overall market.

For instance if the stock price of a companie increased by 5 percent and if the S&P 500 increased by 2 percent in the same period, then the normalized percentage change will be 3 percent. Without this normalization, our model might e.g. perform noticeably better when classifying percentage increases during time periods where the S&P 500 was increasing. However, this might not generalize for time periods where the S&P 500 is decreasing.

The data of the S&P 500 is taken from yahoo finance (https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/%5EGSPC/history).

The target variable Y_cont, was computed as the percentage change from the closing price of the day before the 8-K filing to the opening price of the day after the 8-K filing. Therefore, we compute the equivalent percentage change of the S&P 500 for each 8-K filings. Then, we subtract the percentage changes of the S&P 500 from the percentage changes of the stock prices.

In [0]:
# Compute the S&P 500 percentage changes
for i, row in df_target.iterrows():
    date = row["Date Filed"]
    idx = df_sp[df_sp["Date"] == date].index[0]
    df_sub = df_sp.iloc[range(idx - 1, idx + 2), :].reset_index()
    df_target.loc[i, "sp_500"] = round((df_sub.loc[2, "Open"] - df_sub.loc[0, "Close"])/df_sub.loc[0, "Close"], 4)

Number of Documents per Token

For each token, we compute the number of documents in which the token occurs. Then, we plot the distribution of the number of documents per token. We can see that the majority of tokens only occurs in a small percentage of documents and that relatively few tokens occur in a large percentage of documents.

# Majority class: almost 20% since 5 classes are almost equally frequent
unique, pos = np.unique(y_tr, return_inverse=True)

maxpos = counts.argmax()

8.4 Grid Search: n-grams (after removing irrelevant features)¶

Before computing n-grams, we need to remove certain (irrelevant) tokens because otherwise the fill size will exceed the memory. Hence, the features with a feature importance of smaller than 0.001 according to CatBoost are removed from the text before applying the TfidfVectorizer with n-grams.

print('Preparing embedding matrix.')

# prepare embedding matrix
word_index = tokenizer.word_index
num_words = min(MAX_NUM_WORDS, len(word_index) + 1)
embedding_matrix = np.zeros((num_words, EMBEDDING_DIM))
for word, i in word_index.items():
    if i >= MAX_NUM_WORDS:
        continue
    embedding_vector = embeddings_index.get(word)
    if embedding_vector is not None:
        # words not found in embedding index will be all-zeros.
        embedding_matrix[i] = embedding_vector
        
print("Shape embedding_matrix: {}".format(embedding_matrix.shape))

Preparing embedding matrix.
Shape embedding_matrix: (10000, 100)

# load pre-trained word embeddings into an Embedding layer
# note that we set trainable = False so as to keep the embeddings fixed
embedding_layer = Embedding(input_dim=num_words,
                            output_dim=EMBEDDING_DIM,
                            embeddings_initializer=Constant(embedding_matrix),
                            input_length=MAX_SEQUENCE_LENGTH, 
                            trainable = True)

In [0]:
def RNN():
    inputs = Input(shape=(MAX_SEQUENCE_LENGTH,), dtype='int32')
    layer = embedding_layer(inputs)
    layer = LSTM(128)(layer)
    layer = Dense(256,activation='relu')(layer)
    layer = Dropout(0.5)(layer)
    layer = Dense(5,activation='softmax')(layer)
    model = Model(inputs=inputs,outputs=layer)
    return model

model = RNN()
model.summary()
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',optimizer='adam',metrics=['accuracy'])

10.1 Model Performance in Relation to SIC Domain, Business Location, 8K-event, Ticker Symbol¶

Note that for each of these categories (SIC Domain, Business Location, 8K-event, Ticker Symbol), two plots were created.

  • The first plot shows the distribution of the counts for wrong and correct classifications (separately) across the levels of the categorical variable (in percentages). This means that the sum of all percentage values for correct_classification adds to 100 percent and that the sum of all percentage values for wrong_classification adds to 100 percent. In other words, we compare two distributions.
  • The second plot shows the total (absolute) number of correct and wrong classifications per level of the categorical variable. In some cases, we don't notice a strong difference between correct and false classifications in the first plot but we do in the second plot.

In practice, the second plot is what we might care about the most. This is because we would, in practice make a classification for e.g. an 8K-filing corresponding to a specific 8K-event or a specic SIC domain or a specific business location. Hence, we are interested in the past performance of the model for this specific categorical level, and would therefore like to know the number of correct and wrong classifications for this level for the test data.

10.1.1 All test data¶

First, the plots are created using all observations in the test data, no matter what classification was done for these observations. Note that these visualizations may give you an overly pessimistic view of the model. The visualizations include cases in which we would not actually conduct any trades. As of right now, we might only consider any trades when the model classified a large increase (lg_inc). Hence, in section 10.1.2 these classifications are analyzed in more detail.

10.1.2 Only test data classified as lg_inc¶

Here, we only consider test data observations that were classified as lg_inc. We can think of these test observations as cases, where we might have taken a long position because the model predicted a large increase. After taking the trade, we would have observed the actual change in the stock price: lg_inc, sm_inc, zero might have been acceptable for us since we would not have lost any money (or only little money in the zero category). sm_dec and in particular lg_dec would have given us a loss. In other words, we want to avoid the misclassifications of sm_dec and lg_dec as lg_inc.

10.2 Feature Importance¶

The features are sorted by their feature importance (see https://catboost.ai/docs/concepts/fstr.html and https://catboost.ai/docs/concepts/python-reference_catboostclassifier_get_feature_importance.html).

In [0]:
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names()
df_feat = pd.DataFrame({'Feature': feature_names, "Feature Id": list(range(len(feature_names)))})
df_feat_imp = best_model.get_feature_importance(type = "FeatureImportance",
                                           prettified = True)
df_feat_imp["Feature Id"] = df_feat_imp["Feature Id"].astype(int)

df_feat = pd.merge(df_feat, df_feat_imp, on = "Feature Id")
df_feat = df_feat.sort_values("Importances", ascending = False)

10.3 Backtesting¶

10.3.1 Trade for every lg_inc classfication¶

We might want to know: How much profit/loss would we have realized if we had placed trades whenever the model classified a large increase, i.e. lg_inc. For this purpose, we make the following simplifying assumptions.

  • Commission per trade: 0 USD
  • Cash in portfolio: enough to place any trade
  • Percent of portfolio that is used for 1 trade: 10% (i.e. 2K USD)
  • Percentage of tickers that are tradable: 100%
  • Percentage of trades that are executed fully: 100%
  • Max. loss of 1 trade: 5% (i.e. 100 USD)
  • Max. percentage change realized in case of increase: 50%

Note that the latter assumption is because some proportion of the percentage change might have taken place before we can enter the trade (e.g. pre-market outside of the market trading hours). Further note that the "max. loss of 1 trade" assumption reflects a stop loss. It assumes that we would and can cut our losses on a trade short - if the percentage change is negative.

df_sub = df_te.copy()

df_sub.loc[:, "result"] = 0
df_sub.loc[df_sub["Y_cont"] > 0, "result"] = df_sub[df_sub["Y_cont"] > 0].Y_cont * 2000 * 0.5
df_sub.loc[df_sub["Y_cont"] < 0, "result"] = np.maximum(df_sub[df_sub["Y_cont"] < 0].Y_cont, -0.05) * 2000
df_sub.loc[:, "Date Filed"] = pd.to_datetime(df_sub.loc[:, "Date Filed"])
df_sub = df_sub.sort_values("Date Filed")
df_sub.loc[:, "result_cumulative"] = df_sub.loc[:, "result"].cumsum()
